Tom,<p>
I was one of those who carried a National Liberation Front (NLF)* flag (or marched with those who did). I supported the belief that the NLF represented the majority of the people in Vietnam and were the the only political body that had any right to represent the Vietnamese people. While I supported this position, I also supported ending the war, bringing the troops home, peace in Vietnam through cease-fire and negotiation... 
<p>
I think that an underlying issue is how one sees him/herself in the world. I do not think of myself as primarily a citizen of the US.  This is relevant to me, but more I view myself as a part of a worldwide humanity. This is not political, but rather a recognition of what moves me and what I respond to. I don't get a warm spot in my heart when I salute the flag or hear the "Star Spangled Banner." My love for the US government and its policies were beaten out of me (physically and mentally) in the '60s. 
<p>
It is only since the post-Vietnam War years that I have been able to separate my bitterness about the government from my love of the US people. I support the people of the US but still find myself constantly opposed to the US government policies at home and on the international front. To get back to the issue, I support the rights of people as I see them, in this cast the right of the NLF to represent the Vietnamese people. I supported the soldiers by trying to get them out of the war.
<p>
When people ask me if the choices I made, including not starting a career path until my mid-thirties, working for low pay or no pay jobs, etc., was worth it, I usually say that what I did, over the years might add up to saving the life of one person. If this is true then what I did was cetrtainly worth it and the right move. I hope I would do it again.
<p>
