I have to weigh in on the issue of Jane Fonda.  I have always been perplexed why she has borne the brunt of veterans' anger at the anti-war movement and think scratching the surface here may reveal larger unhealed wounds.
<p>
First, I do want to hear more about how her actions were experienced by soldiers on the ground.  I don't remember particulars about her visit(s) to Vietnam. But she was not, by far, the only American who traveled to North Vietnam during the war.  Ramsey Clark and the Berrigans (I believe) went, the Quakers (American Friends) sent delegations.  
<p>
Why did they go?  My sense is that these delegations were horrified by the destruction that was being wrought (in their name) on the country and people of Vietnam.  They went to take medical supplies, they went to express human compassion and (perhaps naively) to seek an end to war... to save both Vietnamese and American lives!  They were seen by some as giving comfort and support to "the enemy", but I think the point is that they (we) did not accept the characterization of the Vietnamese people as "the enemy". 
<p>
By then we felt that the American government were the aggressors.  We felt that the bombing, napalming, deforestation, anti-personnel bombing, etc., bordered on war crimes and had to be stopped.  (I emphasize that - Lt.Calley not withstanding - most people saw this "war crime" in terms of the effects of a huge political/industrial/military machine, not in the acts of individual soldiers.)
<p>
Now, Jane Fonda.  My memory is that within the anti-war movement, she was seen as a kind of a latecomer and had some trouble overcoming her actress/Barbarella image.  I think she came to her anti-war politics largely through her contacts and personal relationship with Tom Hayden*.  Still, that does not diminish the fact that she was willing to put her personal celebrity at the service of the anti-war cause.  I think she did it sincerely and I think she learned fast.
<p>
The "FTA" or Free the Army Tours (or, more colloquially, F*ck the Army), which
have been mentioned here, were concerts staged near major bases for the entertainment of GI's.  They included Fonda, Holly Near, and other performers.  They were very pro-GI, but they were also very anti-war. The goal was, at least in part,  to show the soldiers that the anti-war movement supported them and to convince GIs to oppose the war.
<p>
The Indochina Peace Campaign was, I think, a spin off-from FTA.  It was a national campaign lead by Fonda and Hayden to take the anti-war message to every  little city and town in the US.  When they came to Ohio in 1972, we took them to state fairs, county fairs, movie theaters... wherever we could. And we worked them to death.  They definitely helped us bring the discussion to new ears (and older ears who were sick of hearing about the war). People may have come because of Jane's celebrity, but they stayed to hear the message:  This war is wrong.  It is not good for the US and it is terrible for the Vietnamese. The Vietnamese are not our enemy.  Vietnam is their country.  We should come home and let them work out their own destiny.
<p>
So, I guess my final question is: if one felt this way, what were the limits on honorable actions to end the war?  As college students, we sometimes (maybe overdramatically) put it in terms of the holocaust.  The government was carrying out genocide in Vietnam and if we didn't do something, we were being "good Germans."  But what to do?  Demonstrations seemed to have limited impact  and political efforts to end the war were stymied.  It is not surprising to me that people went to extreme lengths.  I can even see, though I don't sanction, how some elements of the left turned to violent acts to confront the government.
<p>
But, to come back to Jane Fonda - what exactly is unforgiveable is what she did?  Why did she earn the honored place on so many vicious bumper stickers? And what does that say to the rest of us who came to empathize with the Vietnamese people and did not want the US to "win" the war? 
<p>
Peace,<br>
