Tony, 
<p>
What Jane Fonda did was to jeopardize the well-being, and perhaps the lives, of American POWs in North Vietnam for her own publicity and self-promotion.  Her stunts to try to show how "humane" the North Vietnamese were in their treatment of American POWs brought more beatings to those people, and more hardship.  Her taking of letters which were to be delivered to families by the International Red Cross (IRC) also jeopardized the POWs, and helped the North Vietnamese to delay visits by the IRC of their prison facilities.  I still am not at liberty to specify exactly how this action jeopardized those POWs, but you must understand that she was not operating in their best interests during her visit. Many GIs understand this, and know she wasn't looking out for our best interests.
<p>
Jane Fonda represented to many of us the worst in giving aid and comfort to the North Vietnamese, and yes, a lot of people in the service figured they were "the enemy."  The reason, they were shooting at us, trying to kill us directly or knock us out of the sky.
<p>
What is interesting to me is that you in the protest movement felt that we were the aggressor, when we were trying mostly to interdict supplies on the Ho Chi Mihn Trail (which looked from the air like a freeway).  These supplies were headed through Laos and Cambodia to South Vietnam, to shoot at our forces.  The bombing was not indiscriminate, as it was in WWII.  We hit bridges, supply depots, truck enplacements, etc.  President Johnson wouldn't let us hit ships in the harbor, or even enplacements which were close to civilian areas.  How does this behavior stack up to the protest movements' expressions of it in terms of the holocaust?  This doesn't give the protest movement much credibility with me.
<p>
